\subsection{The sonic point}
Although a critical point is a
mathematical notion
defined on the phase space $(r,n)$ 
of a dynamical system, 
this also is closely related to a physical entity, a sonic point.
We define a sonic point and see its relation with a critical point in the following.
\subsubsection{The transonic flow and the sonic point}
In an accretion problem, one may expect that the fluid particle at infinity,
which falls with small 3-velocity, becomes faster and faster as approaching the source of the gravity.
If the acceleration is sufficient, the velocity, initially smaller than its local sound speed $v_s^2$ (subsonic) at infinity, would become greater than $v_s^2$ (supersonic) at the point near the source.
Such a fluid flow is said to be {\it transonic} and here we call any flow which has both sub- and supersonic regions transonic.
Since, in our accretion problem, a fluid accretion flow is a solution orbit of Eq.~(\ref{eq23}),
we define a {\it sonic point} of a transonic flow as follows.
\begin{definition}
For a stationary and spherically symmetric accretion flow on the spacetime (\ref{eq:metric}), let $n=n(r)$ be the corresponding solution orbit on the phase space $(r,n)$.
Let $v=v(r)$ be the 3-velocity of the fluid measured by static observers.
A sonic point $(r_s,n_s)$ of the accretion flow is defined as a point on the phase space satisfying the condition,
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{v^2}{v_s^2}\right|_{(r_s,n(r_s))}=1,
\end{eqnarray}
where $n_s=n(r_s)$.
\end{definition}
\subsubsection{The sonic point and the critical point}
The critical point mentioned above is closely related to the sonic point and we have the statement about that.
\begin{lemma}{\label{{lemma:sonic-critical}}}
Assume the EOS of the fluid satisfies the condition
\begin{eqnarray}
{\label{{eq:subluminal}}}
&0<v_s^2(n)<1,\\
{\label{{eq:monoinc}}}
&\partial_n v_s^2(n)\ge0.
\end{eqnarray}
That is, the sound speed of the fluid is subluminal and monotonically increasing with respect to $n$.
For a physical transonic accretion flow in our accretion problem, its sonic point coincides with a critical point on
the phase space.
And the critical point is a saddle point.
\end{lemma}
